<subSubSection box="[162,438,1147,1168]" pageId="1" pageNumber="838" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="1.[162,768,392,1863]" box="[162,438,1147,1168]" pageId="1" pageNumber="838">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[162,175,1147,1168]" pageId="1" pageNumber="838">•</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[187,658,1147,1168]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="838">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlussky" authorityYear="1996" box="[187,322,1147,1168]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Haidomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Haidomyrmex</taxonomicName>
scimitarus, 
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="838" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[162,768,392,1863]" pageId="1" pageNumber="838">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlussky" authorityYear="1996" box="[448,583,1147,1168]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Haidomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Haidomyrmex</taxonomicName>
zigrasi Barden &amp; Grimaldi – reconstructions based on two entirely complete dealate (
<emphasis box="[272,405,1208,1229]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="838">H. scimitarus</emphasis>
) and worker (
<emphasis box="[551,649,1208,1229]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="838">H. zigrasi</emphasis>
) specimens suggested that the enigmatic L-shaped mandibles probably articulated, at least partially, in a vertical plane. In particular, the placement of trigger hairs on the clypeus as well as the hypognathous-like orientation of the head (all other non-haidomyrmecine ant heads are prognathous; 
<bibRefCitation author="Keller, R. A." journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History" pageId="1" pageNumber="838" pagination="1 - 90" part="355" refString="Keller, R. A. (2011) A phylogenetic analysis of ant morphology (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) with special reference to the poneromorph subfamilies. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 355, 1 - 90." title="A phylogenetic analysis of ant morphology (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) with special reference to the poneromorph subfamilies" type="journal article" year="2011">Keller, 2011</bibRefCitation>
) suggested that hell ants were Cretaceous analogues to modern trap-jaw predators (
<bibRefCitation author="Barden, P. &amp; Grimaldi, D." box="[493,757,1419,1440]" journalOrPublisher="American Museum Novitates" pageId="1" pageNumber="838" pagination="1 - 16" part="3755" refString="Barden, P. &amp; Grimaldi, D. (2012) Rediscovery of the bizarre Cretaceous ant Haidomyrmex Dlussky (Hymenoptera: Formicidae), with two new species. American Museum Novitates, 3755, 1 - 16." title="Rediscovery of the bizarre Cretaceous ant Haidomyrmex Dlussky (Hymenoptera: Formicidae), with two new species" type="journal article" year="2012">Barden &amp; Grimaldi, 2012</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[187,316,1449,1470]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="838">H. scimitarus</emphasis>
is also the largest haidomyrmecine, measuring over twice the total length of most other species.
</paragraph>
